##### Balanced Search Tree

###### 2-3 Trees

* Allow 1 or 2 keys per node
  * 2-node: one key, two children
  * 3-node: two keys, three children
* Symmetric order: Inorder traversal yields keys in ascending order

---

* Search: 三节点中间 link 在两个 keys 之间
* Insert: 保持完美平衡性
  * 可能会出现**临时性**的 4-node，只需要将 4-node 分解，弄一个到父节点上，其他两个变成 2-node （局部的变化）
  * 向上生长

---

* Time: $\log N \sim \lg N \Rightarrow O(\lg N)$
  * Quite remarkable

To maintain 2-3 tree is complex, so we won't implement it.

###### Red-Black BSTs

> Left-leaning red-black BSTs: Perfect black balance
>
> * 红链接均为左链接
> * 没有任何一个结点同时和两条红链接相连
> * 完美黑色平衡
>   * 每一个红黑树和相应的 2-3 树是一一对应的
>
> A red-black tree tracks every simple path from a node to a descendant leaf with the same number of black nodes they got that right.

1. Represent 2-3 tree as a BST
2. Use "Internal" left-leaning links as "glue" for 3-nodes (larger key is "root")

---

* Data Structure

```java
private class Node {
    Key key;
    Value val;
    Node left, right;
    boolean color; // color of parent link
}
```

---

* `get`
  * just like the elementary BST (ignore color)
* rotation: 某些操作中可能出现右红链接或者两条红链接，我们需要将其旋转形成标准红黑树
  * 有时候，我们也会需要暂时使用右旋

![](data:image/png;base64,)

```java
private Node rotateLeft(Node h) {
    Node x = h.right;
    h.right = x.left;
    x.left = h;
    x.color = h.color;
    h.color = RED;
    return x;
}
```

* Color flip: Recolor to split a (temporary) 4-node
  * just change colors

---

* Basic strategy: Maintain 1-1 correspondence with 2-3 trees by applying elementary red-black BST operations
* `put`
  * Case 1: insert into a 2-node at bottom
    * std BST insert; color new link red
    * rotate left if red link is right
  * Case 2: Insert into a 3-node at bottom
    * Do std BST insert; color new link red
    * Rotate to balance the 4-node (if needed)
    * Flip colors to pass red link up one level
    * Rotate to make lean left (if needed)
    * Repeat case 1 or case 2 up the tree (if needed)
* `remove` is difficult to implement

---

Height of tree is $\le 2 \lg N$ in the worst case

###### B-Trees

* Generalize 2-3 trees by allowing up to  $M-1$  key-link pairs per node
  * At least 2 key-link pairs at root
  * At least $M /2$ kys-link pairs in other nodes
  * External nodes contain client keys
  * Internal nodes contain copies of keys to guide search

##### Geometric Applications of BSTs

###### 1d range search

* Extension of ordered ST
  * Insert k-v pair
  * Search for key $k$
  * Delete key $k$
  * Range search: find all keys between $k_1\ \text{and} \ k_2$
  * Range count: number of keys between
* Application: Database queries
* Geometric interpretation: Key are point on a line

---

* Implementations
  * Unordered array: Fast insert, slow range search
  * Ordered array: Slow insert, binary search
  * BST: $O(\log N)$

###### Line segment intersection

> 线段都是正交的，要么水平，要么垂直

* Sweep-line algorithm
  * sweep vertical line from left to right
    * x-coordinates defines events
    * h-segment(left endpoint): insert y-coordinates into BST
    * h-segment(right endpointa0: remove y-coordinate from BST
    * v-segment: **range search** for interval of y-endpoints
  * Time: $N\log N + R$
    * $R$ intersection
    * $N$ orthogonal line segments

###### Kd Trees

> An extension of BST, to deal with points in geometric space efficiently.

* Geometric interpretation
  * Keys are point in the plane
  * Find/count points in a given h-v rectangle

---

* Grid implementation
* Space-time tradeoff:
  * Space: $M^2+N$
  * Time: $1 + N / M^2$ per square examined, onaverage

Usually points is not randomly distributed, there is clustering phenomenon.

---

* 2d tree implementation: Recursively divide space into two halfplanes
  * Data structure: BST, using x- and y-coordinates as key
    * search gives gives rectangle containing point
    * insert further subdivides the plane
  * Range search
    * check if point in node lies in given rectangle
    * recursively search left/bottom (if any could fall in rectangle)
    * recursively search right/top (if any could fall in rectangle)
    * Time: $R+\log N$
      * worst: $R + \sqrt{N}$
  * nearest neighbor search
    * check distance point in node to query point
    * Recursively search left/bottom (if it could contain a closer point)
    * Recursively search right/top (if it could contain a closer point)
    * organize method so that it begins by searching for query point
    * Time: $\log N$
      * Worst: $N$

###### interval search tree

> 区间搜索树

* Use left endpoint as BST key
* store max endpoint in sub tree rooted at node

---

* insert (lo, hi)
  * Insert into BST, using lo as the key
  * Update max in each node on search path
* Search (lo, hi): search for any *one* interval that intersects (lo, hi) 
  * if interval in node intersects query interval, return it
  * Else if left subtree is null, go right
  * Else if max endpoint in left subtree is less than lo, go right
  * Else go left
